{"title_page": "BGFIBank Group", "text_new": "{{short description|Financial service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = BGFIBank Group\n| logo   = Logo BGFIBank.jpg\n| type   = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation     = 1971\n| location       = [[Libreville]], [[Gabon]]\n| key_people     = '''Patrice Otha''', [[Chairman]]<br/> Henri-Claude Oyima, [[Chief Executive Officer]]\n| industry       = [[Banking]] and [[Finance]]\n| products       = [[Loans]], [[Mortgages]] [[Investments]], [[Debit cards]], [[Credit Cards]] \n| revenue        = \n| assets         =\n| num_employees  = \n| homepage \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 = [https://groupebgfibank.com/   Homepage]\n}}\n\n'''BGFIBank Group''', whose full name is '''BGFIBank Group S.A.''', is a financial services organization headquartered in [[Gabon]]. The group has subsidiaries in eight countries including [[Gabon]], [[Benin]], [[Republic of the Congo]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Madagascar]], [[France]] and [[Cote d'Ivoire]].\n\n==Overview==\nBGFIBank Group is a large financial services [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] in  [[Central Africa|Central]], [[West Africa|West]] and [[East Africa|East]] Africa, with subsidiaries in ten countries. The member institutions serve both individuals and businesses, with emphasis on small-to-medium enterprises (SMEs). As of December 2010, the Group's assets were in excess of \u20ac3.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=12 January 2019 | url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=our-financial-statements&id_article=194|title=2009 Group Financial Statement|publisher=Bgfi.com}}</ref> In January 2010, BGFIGroup was rated the largest bank group in [[Central Africa]], by assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://developmentafrique.com/?tag=groupe-bgfi-bank|title=BGFIBank Group Second Largest Bank Group In Central Africa|access-date=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709020031/http://developmentafrique.com/?tag=groupe-bgfi-bank|archive-date=9 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1971, the group started with one institution in Gabon called '''Bank of Paris and the Netherlands Gabon'''.  That first bank was a joint venture between several  private [[Gabon]]ese investors, [[BNP Paribas]] and the [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=402|title=PNB Paribas Was A Founding Investor In BGFIBank Group|accessdate=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713033320/http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=402|archive-date=13 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe group's first subsidiary was set up in 1987 under the name '''FIGADIM''' and was later renamed [[BGFIBail]]. In 1996, when Gabonese private investors acquired majority shareholding in the bank, it rebranded as the '''International Gabonese and French Bank''' known in [[France|French]],   as    \"Banque Gabonaise et Fran\u00e7aise Internationale\" (BGFI). The Group's second subsidiary, [[Financiere Transafricaine]] (Finatra), was established in 1997.\n\nIn 2000, the bank rebranded to '''BGFIBank S.A.''', which is its current name. During the next ten years, the group has pursued an aggressive expansion policy by opening a subsidiary in [[Republic of the Congo]] in 2000, [[Equatorial Guinea]] in 2001, [[France]] in 2007, [[Madagascar]] in 2010, [[Benin]] in 2010 and [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] in 2010. During the same decade a plethora of non-bank financial subsidiaries were set up by the group, the majority being located in [[Gabon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=background&id_article=182|title=History of BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Member companies==\nThe companies that composes the BGFIBank Group include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=our-activities&id_article=183|title=Subsidiaries of BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Commercial banks\n* [[BGFIBank Cameroon]] - {{flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Cameroon]]\n* [[BGFIBank Gabon]] - {{flagicon|Gabon}} [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBank Guinea]] - {{flagicon|Equatorial Guinea}} [[Equatorial Guinea]]\n* [[BGFIBank International]] - {{flagicon|France}} [[France]]\n* [[BGFIBank Congo]] - {{flagicon|Congo}} [[Republic of Congo]]\n* [[BGFIBank Madagascar]] - {{flagicon|Madagascar}} [[Madagascar]]\n* [[BGFIBank Benin]] - {{flagicon|Benin}} [[Benin]]\n* [[BGFIBank DRC]] - {{flagicon|Democratic Republic of the Congo}} [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n\n; Other financial services companies\n* [[BGFI Immo]] - Real estate business - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFI Asset Management]] - Portfolio management - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBail]] - Leasing - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBourse]] - Financial engineering, stockbroking and consultancy - {{flagicon|Gabon}} [[Gabon]] \n* [[Finatra]] - Consumer credit - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFICash]] - Funds transfer - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIFactor]] - Factoring - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[LOXIA Emf]] - Microfinance - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[Socofin]] - Leasing and consumer credit {{flagicon|Congo}} [[Republic of the Congo]]\n\n==Ownership==\nShareholding in the Group's stock is private, although dynamic. New investors can buy in, while existing investors have the opportunity to divest. However, the Group's stock is not listed on any publicly traded exchange. The detailed shareholding in BGFIBank Group is illustrated in the table below:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?id_article=177|title=Shareholding In BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n| width=\"100%\" align=\"center\" | '''BGFIBank Group stock ownership'''\n|- valign=\"top\" \n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n! style=\"width:2em;\" |Rank !!Name of owner!!Percentage ownership\n|-\n|1||Private investors||32.50\n|-\n|2||Gabon Development Bank||10.00\n|-\n|3||Delta Synergie ||09.01\n|-\n|4||Financi\u00e9re des Vosges ||05.00\n|-\n|5||Compagnie du Komo||25.01\n|-\n|6||Carlo Tassara Asset Management||09.50\n|-\n|7||BGFIBank employees||08.98\n|-\n| ||'''Total'''||'''100.00'''\n|}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Governance==\nThe [[Chairman]] of the eleven member [[Board of Directors]] is Patrice Otha. The [[Chief Executive Officer]] of the Group is Henri-Claude Oyima and the General Secretary is Brice Laccruche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=bgfibank-top-management&id_article=186|title=Key People At BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n* [[List of banks in Gabon]]\n* [[List of banks in Africa]]\n* [[Central Bank of Central African States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bgfi.com/ Website of BGFIBank Group] (French) & (English)\n* [http://www.beac.int/ Website of Central Bank of Central African States (French)]\n* [http://www.afdevinfo.com/htmlreports/org/org_41378.html Company Profile At Afdevinfo.com]\n\n[[Category:Banks of Gabon]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Libreville]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Financial service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = BGFIBank Group\n| logo   = Logo BGFIBank.jpg\n| type   = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation     = 1971\n| location       = [[Libreville]], [[Gabon]]\n| key_people     = '''Patrice Otha''', [[Chairman]]<br/> Henri-Claude Oyima, [[Chief Executive Officer]]\n| industry       = [[Banking]] and [[Finance]]\n| products       = [[Loans]], [[Mortgages]] [[Investments]], [[Debit cards]], [[Credit Cards]] \n| revenue        = \n| assets         =\n| num_employees  = \n| homepage \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 = [https://groupebgfibank.com/ Homepage]\n}}\n\n'''BGFIBank Group''', whose full name is '''BGFIBank Group S.A.''', is a financial services organization headquartered in [[Gabon]]. The group has subsidiaries in eight countries including [[Gabon]], [[Benin]], [[Republic of the Congo]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Equatorial Guinea]], [[Madagascar]], [[France]] and [[Cote d'Ivoire]].\n\n==Overview==\nBGFIBank Group is a large financial services [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] in  [[Central Africa|Central]], [[West Africa|West]] and [[East Africa|East]] Africa, with subsidiaries in ten countries. The member institutions serve both individuals and businesses, with emphasis on small-to-medium enterprises (SMEs). As of December 2010, the Group's assets were in excess of \u20ac3.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=12 January 2019 | url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=our-financial-statements&id_article=194|title=2009 Group Financial Statement|publisher=Bgfi.com}}</ref> In January 2010, BGFIGroup was rated the largest bank group in [[Central Africa]], by assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://developmentafrique.com/?tag=groupe-bgfi-bank|title=BGFIBank Group Second Largest Bank Group In Central Africa|access-date=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709020031/http://developmentafrique.com/?tag=groupe-bgfi-bank|archive-date=9 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1971, the group started with one institution in Gabon called '''Bank of Paris and the Netherlands Gabon'''.  That first bank was a joint venture between several  private [[Gabon]]ese investors, [[BNP Paribas]] and the [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=402|title=PNB Paribas Was A Founding Investor In BGFIBank Group|accessdate=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713033320/http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=402|archive-date=13 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe group's first subsidiary was set up in 1987 under the name '''FIGADIM''' and was later renamed [[BGFIBail]]. In 1996, when Gabonese private investors acquired majority shareholding in the bank, it rebranded as the '''International Gabonese and French Bank''' known in [[France|French]],   as    \"Banque Gabonaise et Fran\u00e7aise Internationale\" (BGFI). The Group's second subsidiary, [[Financiere Transafricaine]] (Finatra), was established in 1997.\n\nIn 2000, the bank rebranded to '''BGFIBank S.A.''', which is its current name. During the next ten years, the group has pursued an aggressive expansion policy by opening a subsidiary in [[Republic of the Congo]] in 2000, [[Equatorial Guinea]] in 2001, [[France]] in 2007, [[Madagascar]] in 2010, [[Benin]] in 2010 and [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] in 2010. During the same decade a plethora of non-bank financial subsidiaries were set up by the group, the majority being located in [[Gabon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=background&id_article=182|title=History of BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Member companies==\nThe companies that composes the BGFIBank Group include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?chaine=our-activities&id_article=183|title=Subsidiaries of BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Commercial banks\n* [[BGFIBank Cameroon]] - {{flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Cameroon]]\n* [[BGFIBank Gabon]] - {{flagicon|Gabon}} [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBank Guinea]] - {{flagicon|Equatorial Guinea}} [[Equatorial Guinea]]\n* [[BGFIBank International]] - {{flagicon|France}} [[France]]\n* [[BGFIBank Congo]] - {{flagicon|Congo}} [[Republic of Congo]]\n* [[BGFIBank Madagascar]] - {{flagicon|Madagascar}} [[Madagascar]]\n* [[BGFIBank Benin]] - {{flagicon|Benin}} [[Benin]]\n* [[BGFIBank DRC]] - {{flagicon|Democratic Republic of the Congo}} [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n\n; Other financial services companies\n* [[BGFI Immo]] - Real estate business - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFI Asset Management]] - Portfolio management - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBail]] - Leasing - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIBourse]] - Financial engineering, stockbroking and consultancy - {{flagicon|Gabon}} [[Gabon]] \n* [[Finatra]] - Consumer credit - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFICash]] - Funds transfer - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[BGFIFactor]] - Factoring - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[LOXIA Emf]] - Microfinance - {{flagicon|Gabon}} - [[Gabon]]\n* [[Socofin]] - Leasing and consumer credit {{flagicon|Congo}} [[Republic of the Congo]]\n\n==Ownership==\nShareholding in the Group's stock is private, although dynamic. New investors can buy in, while existing investors have the opportunity to divest. However, the Group's stock is not listed on any publicly traded exchange. The detailed shareholding in BGFIBank Group is illustrated in the table below:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/en/article.php?id_article=177|title=Shareholding In BGFIBank Group|publisher=|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n| width=\"100%\" align=\"center\" | '''BGFIBank Group stock ownership'''\n|- valign=\"top\" \n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n! style=\"width:2em;\" |Rank !!Name of owner!!Percentage ownership\n|-\n|1||Private investors||32.50\n|-\n|2||Gabon Development Bank||10.00\n|-\n|3||Delta Synergie ||09.01\n|-\n|4||Financi\u00e9re des Vosges ||05.00\n|-\n|5||Compagnie du Komo||25.01\n|-\n|6||Carlo Tassara Asset Management||09.50\n|-\n|7||BGFIBank employees||08.98\n|-\n| ||'''Total'''||'''100.00'''\n|}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Governance==\nThe [[Chairman]] of the eleven member [[Board of Directors]] is Patrice Otha. The [[Chief Executive Officer]] of the Group is Henri-Claude Oyima and the General Secretary is Brice Laccruche.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgfi.com/site/